2022 was all about my personal practice of self-love. This past year was all about love for myself and the things I enjoy most. I re-read All About Love by Bell Hooks this time last year and promised myself to make my year all about love. This meant more adventure, setting better boundaries, prioritizing rest, having more fun, spending more time on my own, and surrounding myself with people that I feel my best around. My all about love Year brought me back to myself and the places I love, like Iceland and Amsterdam, it also pulled me away from environments that I didn’t love so much. 

2021 was a doozy. Heartbreak. Hard lessons. Sugar coating just downright bad experiences. I want more and need much more out of life. So, this year I focused on what I could control. There was no vision board or lists of intentions. There was just a brilliant book with a bright red cover, All About Love, and this quote below: 

“Self-love is the foundation of our loving practice. Without it our other efforts to love fail. Giving ourselves love we provide our inner being with the opportunity to have the unconditional love we may have always longed to receive from someone else.” — Bell Hooks

2022 was a year dedicated to building the foundation that’s all about (self) love ❤️ 2023 will be about letting it continue to flourish and grow.

That time I was featured in Forbes (?!?!)

I’m trying to get better at sharing my wins. Being featured in @forbes last year was one of them. Gratitude and love to @pauleannareid for expertly capturing my experience as a founder with honesty and care.

My journey to entrepreneurship wasn’t an intentional one. Like most racialized women, it came from a place of necessity. I just wanted a job where I could pay my bills and feel safe doing it. Sadly, entrepreneurship (despite all of the ups and downs that come along with it) feels less stressful than navigating the traditional workplace. I never imagined Forbes would be interested in sharing my story as a founder — but here we are. I believe the work we are doing at @buildwithbloom is inspiring industry-wide changes. It’s hard work to encourage leaders to slow down, build with intention, and evolve legacy ways of working. But we are doing it. 

For millennia capitalism has shaped the way we work — and it’s no surprise that work doesn’t work for most of us because of it. I’ve spent my entire career trying to make work, work for me. I think I’ve made that happen for myself — now I’m on a mission to help companies craft workplaces that can work for everyone. Accomplishments like this wouldn’t be possible without the support of the collective team at Bloom, past team members that have embarked on exciting new professional journeys, our community who consistently amplify our work in spaces we aren’t in, and the values-aligned companies we partner with. Thank you for supporting me and the collective team at Bloom as we grow.

PSA: Bloom is a full-service workplace design company that offers fractional DEI, HR, and Recruitment support to organizations that want to feel good about their growth. We are the only firm that takes an anti-oppressive approach across every aspect of the employee journey. Whether you’re building out your marketing team, crafting an employee handbook, or want to offer DEI training to your team — we’ve got you covered ❤️

Women’s History Month starts today. We’ve crafted three high-impact sessions to help you celebrate with intention.

I lost my why.

I started my company Bloom in 2019. My why was clear then. After climbing the corporate ladder, I left the high-paying tech job I loved because I was assaulted at work. I struggled to find my footing in traditional workplaces after that experience. In some ways, it was the trauma in other ways, it was the system of work altogether. I asked myself often — if we all need to work to survive, why can’t work, work for all of us? So, I decided to enable companies to build and scale companies that could work for everyone. That’s my why. My why led me to take what was a lucrative solo-consulting business where I was earning $50,000 a month to build a team. I knew if I wanted to go far with my mission, my why, I would go further with a team than alone. Even if it meant more stress and less money. I fundamentally believe we go further together than we do alone. Building a company through a global pandemic, budding recession, economic uncertainty, and mental health crisis has been challenging and, at times dehumanizing.

Since I founded Bloom, I’ve been in a constant state of fear. I started Bloom out of fear of facing more harm at work and pushed through challenging times out of fear that failure could mean returning to the spaces where I experienced so much harm. Fear can be a great motivator, but it’s not a great place to live. Embodying fear made it easy for me to lose my way because fear is far more intense and all-encompassing feeling than my why. 

I cried during @simonsinek talk with @immollybloom because it was during their conversation that I realized I’ve let fear overtake my why. I talk about my why every day, but fear holds me back from embodying it. The community of people I had the opportunity to meet and learn from this weekend reminded me of my why and brought me back to myself in more ways than I can explain. Endless gratitude to all of the people I connected with this weekend who showed up with authenticity, curiosity and love. This experience couldn’t have come at a better time for me. Sending lots of love to @joannaknix who invited me to join her on this exciting experience and @luxuriousroxy who inspired me to wear this iconic fit.

This past week my conversation with @buildwithbloom clients and friends of @girlboss Adrien Bettio and Hyla Nayeri dropped — the women behind the It girl swim and lifestyle brand 437. 

The co-founders met at university while studying commerce, and became fast friends and eventually, roommates. Hyla and Adrien were on a trip in the Amalfi Coast and they couldn't find swimsuits that were flattering and buttery soft. And thus, the idea for 437 was born. They were just 21 years old.

Today, 437 is loved and worn by celebs like Kylie Jenner, Megan Thee Stallion and JLo, and appeared in Vogue and Forbes. Joy feels like knowing our neighbours around the Lake will witness generations of Black and non-white folks connect, relax, and experience happiness in a space we actively face barriers accessing. 

You know this works by design right? The lack of representation of Black folks in the outdoors experiencing adventure and leisure isn’t without intention. As systemic barriers persist, I can't help but acknowledge the hard reality that non-white individuals, particularly Black folks, face when accessing homeownership. It's rare for non-white folks to own homes, let alone second homes, especially places dedicated to leisure. While I feel pride in being the only Black family on the Lake, I am aware of the complexities surrounding the celebration of representation in an area that isn't inherently ours to claim. Owning a cottage comes with privileges, and I acknowledge that these lands have a rich history that predates our ownership. Indigenous peoples have deep connections to these territories, and their stewardship and knowledge deserve recognition and respect.

If you’re a cottage owner, have access to one, or regular cottages throughout the summer I encourage you to learn about the historical and ongoing injustices faced by Indigenous Peoples and support your local Indigenous community with your time, energy, advocacy and dollars.

With all of its complexities, I'll share this: Nature is healing and everyone deserves to enjoy the power of the outdoors in all of its forms. 

Slides 4-6 written by: Elamin Abdelmahoud titled “Breaking the colour code of the Canadian cottage experiences” for @cottagelife

Under a capitalist system and observing the presence of long perpetuated systems of oppression — will real “psychological safety” ever be achieved at work? 

I have never in any workplace (even my own) for a myriad of reasons consistently felt “psychological safety” — as a individual contributor the threat of being fired created a barrier to feeling psychological safety and as a founder and small business owner the reality that most businesses fail has created a similar barrier.

I think the idea of sustained “psychological safety” at work is beautiful—but delusional. I’ve shared my thoughts on why. What are your thoughts? I’ve been thinking about this for weeks—my DM’s are open ♥️

Don’t ever settle. Not with love. Not with your job. Not with your city. Not with your home. Not with your happiness. If something doesn’t feel right, let it go and leave it behind. Even without logical reason, even without knowing what you’ll do next, leave it behind because it just doesn’t matter. If it’s not meant for you, let it bod because one day you’ll thank yourself for never settling on your happiness. One day you’ll realize that you were meant for so much more and that you only found it because you never settled. 

From me you you: Sending love to everyone who refuses to settle. I know it isn’t easy. This is a daily choice that you have to sustain. It takes grit and vision not to settle. It takes patience. It’s hard. It can be lonely. It’s easy to give in. Keep going. Don’t settle.

Honestly, smiling through challenging seasons doesn’t mean you’re ignoring your needs, setting “bad” boundaries or not practicing self care—it may just mean you’re doing what you need to do to survive.

I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again: The system of work wasn’t built with most of us to thrive. For millennia women have had to navigate a system that wasn’t built for them in mind.

My friend (and the panel facilitator) @jodikovitz shared some upsetting stats from a joint report by Accenture and Girls who Code that found 50% of women who take a tech role drop it by the age of 35, compared to approximately 20% in other types of jobs. She then asked me about what factors I believe are contributing to women making these early exits from the tech industry. 

Well, you can listen to my full answer on slide two or get the shorter version below:

Most leaders will speak to the lack of mentorship, pay equity, work life balance, representation or the glass ceiling. But, I think there is a more prevalent experience women have that we never talk about which is isolation, workplace violence, unwanted conduct and harassment. Studies and reports have highlighted that the tech industry has faced higher instances of harassment and discrimination, particularly against women. I think these experiences create a ripple effect of fear and often quietly push our brightest minds out of the industry. I know, because I was one of them.
A different perspective.

Home update 🏡

After three years, my home renovation journey is done. In 2020 I bought my first home and took on the responsibility of making it my own. I absolutely underestimated the stress that would come along with gutting and renovating a heritage home. But, I did it.

I know there are a lot of women who, like me, are waiting around to buy a home once they meet a special someone. This was a limiting belief that held me back from making this big investment—until I asked myself why I couldn’t become a home owner on my own? It’s a classic story of—she believed she could, so she did. 

For millennia, women have faced unique barriers to achieving home ownership. Over the years, we have fought tirelessly for the right to work, vote, have a credit card or own a home. In Canada, there were no specific laws that prohibited women from owning a home. However, it's important to mention that Canada, like many other countries, has a complex history of gender and racial discrimination which affected the ability of people like me, especially women, access home ownership.

Canada has had a long history of discriminatory practices and policies, including racially restrictive covenants, which were clauses in property deeds that prevented the sale of property to individuals of specific racial or ethnic backgrounds. These practices, along with broader systemic racism, disproportionately affected Black Canadians and other racialized communities.

It wasn't until the mid-20th century, when anti-discrimination legislation was introduced, along with legal reforms, that progress was made in addressing racial discrimination and promoting equal housing rights for all Canadians, regardless of race, gender or ethnicity.

All this to say—I bought and gutted my 180 year old century home and it’s been a massive labour of love. Here are a few pictures of what I created.

Last week, I had the privilege and honour to shout "Fuck the patriarchy" alongside thousands other people, mostly women, in Reykjavík during a nationwide strike.

It was an honour to be in Iceland during an unprecedented nationwide strike, where 100,000 people—a remarkable number given Iceland's population of just 370,000—took to the streets to demand equal pay and call for systemic change to end gender-based violence against women and non-binary folks.

I’m not sure if you know this but—even though Iceland is known for its strong commitment to gender equality, it still has one of the highest gender pay gaps in Europe, with women earning around 18% less than their male counterparts. Despite being a leader in gender equality, the people of Iceland are still fighting for better systems, more access to support and meaningful protections for gender diverse folks. 

Iceland is a leader in the fight for equal rights. In 2018, Iceland became the first country in the world to mandate equal pay certification, requiring employers to prove that they pay equal wages for equal work, regardless of gender. Even the current Prime Minister herself participated in the recent strike last week. To me, it was incredible to witness women and non-binary folks still push for more sustained action.

The people of Iceland gathered to address pressing inequalities and stand in solidarity with each other. This strike wasn't just an event; it was a powerful statement of solidarity and a call for a brighter future in a country that has always stood for equity and justice for women, non-binary and gender diverse folks.

As a Canadian in attendance I can say I was really moved by the collective act of solidarity, the emphasis on inclusion and the energy women and non-binary folks brought to the streets that day. To me, this is what real solidarity looks like.
